'''David Ospina Ramírez''' (born 31 August 1988) is a [[Colombia]]n professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Categoría Primera A]] club [[Atlético Nacional]], which he [[Captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]].

Ospina began his career at [[Atlético Nacional]], making his debut with the club in 2005. After achieving two domestic titles with ''Los Verdolagas'', Ospina joined French side [[OGC Nice|Nice]]. In 2014, he joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on a four-year deal. During his time in [[London]], Ospina won three trophies with the club: the [[FA Cup]] in [[2014–15 FA Cup|2015]] and [[2016–17 FA Cup|2017]], as well as the [[2017 FA Community Shield]]. In 2018, Ospina was loaned out to [[Serie A]] club [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]]. The following year, Napoli permanently signed Ospina. In 2020, Ospina played a pivotal role in Napoli's conquering of the [[2019–20 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]]. Following unsuccessful negotiations to renew his contract with Napoli, Ospina signed for [[Saudi Pro League]] side [[Al Nassr FC|Al Nassr]] in 2022. In 2024, he returned to his home country, rejoining Atlético Nacional, with whom he won the [[Copa Colombia]] for the first time in his career.

Ospina has represented his country at a full international level since 2007. At youth level, Ospina represented Colombia at the [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]]. Notably, he was part of the Colombia squads that won gold at the [[2005 Bolivarian Games]] and the [[Football at the 2006 Central American and Caribbean Games|2006 Central American and Caribbean Games]]. Upon his senior debut against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], he became the youngest goalkeeper to make an appearance for Colombia. He has since earned 130 caps for his nation, making him [[Colombia national football team#Most capped players|his nation's most capped player of all time]], appearing at four [[Copa América]]s and two [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]].

== Club career ==
=== Early Career and Rise at Atlético Nacional ===
[[File:David Ospina.jpg|thumb|left|David Ospina with [[Atlético Nacional]] in 2008]]
David Ospina began his professional football career with the youth academy of [[Atlético Nacional]], one of Colombia's most successful clubs, based in his hometown of Medellín. After progressing through the ranks, he made his senior debut in the [[Categoría Primera A]] in 2005 at the age of 17.<ref name="El Tiempo">{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-2826978 |title=Nacional, campeón del fútbol colombiano |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2007-12-19 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elpais.com.co/deporte/futbol/la-historia-del-arco-colombiano-contada-por-sus-grandes-protagonistas-SMEP_387994 |title=La historia del arco colombiano contada por sus grandes protagonistas |publisher=El País (Colombia) |date=2018-03-24 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Ospina made an immediate impact during the [[2005 Categoría Primera A season#Apertura|2005 Torneo Apertura]], becoming a key figure in the Atlético Nacional side that secured the league title under manager [[Santiago Escobar]]. It was his first major trophy, coming just months after his debut, and helped solidify his reputation as a rising talent in Colombian football.<ref name="El Tiempo"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/atletico-nacional-el-equipo-de-los-titulo-en-colombia-articulo-567406/ |title=Atlético Nacional, el equipo de los títulos en Colombia |publisher=El Espectador |date=2015-06-25 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Local sports media began to praise Ospina's agility, composure, and maturity beyond his years.<ref name="El Tiempo"/><ref name="El Espectador">{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/david-ospina-el-arquero-de-las-grandes-ligas-articulo-800262/ |title=David Ospina, el arquero de las grandes ligas |publisher=El Espectador |date=2018-07-06 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

By 2007, Ospina had firmly established himself as Atlético Nacional's first-choice goalkeeper. Under manager [[Óscar Héctor Quintabani]], he was instrumental in helping the team achieve a historic domestic double, winning both the Apertura and Finalización. In the Apertura final, Nacional faced [[Atlético Huila]], with Ospina's strong goalkeeping performances proving decisive in their 2–1 aggregate victory. His contributions in the second leg, played on 17 June 2007, were particularly vital in securing the title.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/cuando-nacional-fue-campeon-con-oscar-quintabani-articulo-567228/ |title=Cuando Nacional fue campeón con Óscar Quintabani |publisher=El Espectador |date=2015-06-25 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-2591605 |title=Nacional ganó la final de la Liga Postobón I-2007 |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2007-06-18 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

=== OGC Nice ===
David Ospina’s six-year tenure at [[OGC Nice]], from 2008 to 2014, was a transformative period that saw the Colombian goalkeeper evolve into one of [[Ligue 1]]’s most reliable shot-stoppers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/football/ligue-1/ogc-nice/ogc-nice-david-ospina-un-heros-discret-3023259 |title=OGC Nice: David Ospina, un héros discret |publisher=Ouest-France |date=2014-07-26 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====Arrival and Early Promise (2008–09)====
Following three standout seasons at [[Atlético Nacional]], Ospina joined OGC Nice in July 2008 for a reported €2 million fee.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Ospina-signe-a-nice/2800 |title=Ospina signe à Nice |publisher=L'Équipe |date=2008-07-16 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He was recruited as the long-term replacement for [[Hugo Lloris]], who had departed for [[Olympique Lyonnais]] in a deal worth €8.5 million. Ospina initially served as backup to [[Lionel Letizi]], using this period to acclimate to European football.

He debuted in the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] on 18 October 2008 and made his [[Ligue 1]] debut a month later. On 17 January 2009, he earned his first league start and clean sheet in a 2–0 home win against [[AJ Auxerre]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nicematin.com/football/ogc-nice-et-si-on-revoyait-les-debuts-de-david-ospina-a-nice-57239 |title=OGC Nice: Et si on revoyait les débuts de David Ospina à Nice ? |publisher=Nice-Matin |date=2018-08-01 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

In a 2–1 away victory over [[FC Lorient]] on 14 February 2009, Ospina’s standout saves were credited with securing the win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/football/ligue-1/2009/02/14/04001-20090214ARTFIG00649-nice-s-impose-a-lorient-.php |title=Nice s'impose à Lorient |publisher=Le Figaro |date=2009-02-14 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

He made 25 appearances in all competitions during the 2008–09 season, recording five clean sheets in Ligue 1.

====Consolidation and Consistency (2009–2012)====
[[File:Ospina1.JPG|thumb|upright|David Ospina playing for Nice in 2013]]
In 2009–10, Ospina became the undisputed first-choice goalkeeper, playing 37 out of 38 Ligue 1 matches and achieving 10 clean sheets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballStats20092010/StatsL1Gardien.html |title=Ligue 1 2009-2010 : Les statistiques des gardiens |publisher=L'Équipe |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Despite Nice’s 15th-place finish, his performances earned him the nickname “the wall of Nice” among local supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nicematin.com/football/il-etait-le-mur-de-l-ogc-nice-les-supporters-rendent-hommage-a-david-ospina-33671 |title=Il était le "mur" de l'OGC Nice: les supporters rendent hommage à David Ospina |publisher=Nice-Matin |date=2014-07-27 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

In 2010–11, under new manager [[Éric Roy]], he improved further, registering 11 clean sheets in 37 Ligue 1 appearances. Key shutouts included a 1–0 win over [[Olympique de Marseille]] on 5 December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nicematin.com/football/ligue-1-nice-bat-marseille-1-0-33670 |title=Ligue 1: Nice bat Marseille (1-0) |publisher=Nice-Matin |date=2010-12-05 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

He repeated this consistency in 2011–12 with another 11 clean sheets over 37 league games. A potential transfer to [[Beşiktaş J.K.]] fell through in summer 2012, to the relief of supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Ospina-le-transfert-tombe-a-l-eau/301757 |title=Ospina : le transfert tombe à l'eau |publisher=L'Équipe |date=2012-08-16 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====Breakthrough Season (2012–13)====
Under new coach [[Claude Puel]], Ospina led Nice to a 5th-place finish and [[UEFA Europa League]] qualification. He kept 11 clean sheets in 26 Ligue 1 appearances, including a 5–0 win over [[Valenciennes FC]] in May 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/football/ligue-1/ligue-1-nice-ecrase-valenciennes-5-0-1205318 |title=Ligue 1. Nice écrase Valenciennes (5-0) |publisher=Ouest-France |date=2013-05-26 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====Final Season and Farewell (2013–14)====
In his final season at Nice, Ospina made 29 Ligue 1 appearances and posted 13 clean sheets—the highest of his time at the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballStats20132014/StatsL1Gardien.html |title=Ligue 1 2013-2014 : Les statistiques des gardiens |publisher=L'Équipe |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He starred in a 1–0 win against [[Olympique de Marseille]] on 18 October 2013, making several key saves.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sport/article/2013/10/18/ligue-1-l-om-chute-a-nice_3500206_3242.html |title=Ligue 1: L'OM chute à Nice |publisher=Le Monde |date=2013-10-18 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Despite Nice finishing 17th, Ospina’s performances drew praise and ultimately led to his transfer to [[Arsenal F.C.]] in July 2014 for £3 million.<ref name="BBC Sport">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/28514580 |title=David Ospina: Arsenal sign Colombia goalkeeper from Nice |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2014-07-27 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Across six seasons, Ospina made 199 appearances for Nice, including 189 in Ligue 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Ospina-nice-c-est-termine/485984 |title=Ospina: Nice, c'est terminé |publisher=L'Équipe |date=2014-07-27 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He remains widely regarded as one of the club’s top keepers, earning the “Aiglon Crédit Agricole” Player of the Season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nicematin.com/football/david-ospina-elu-aiglon-credit-agricole-de-la-saison-78560 |title=David Ospina élu Aiglon Crédit Agricole de la saison |publisher=Nice-Matin |date=2014-05-18 |language=fr |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

=== Arsenal ===
====2014–15 season====
On 27 July 2014, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] confirmed that Ospina had signed for the club for an undisclosed fee, reported to be £3 million, on a four-year contract.<ref name="BBC Sport"/> He was assigned the number 13 shirt, previously worn by [[Emiliano Viviano]].
[[File:David Ospina, Petr Cech Emiliano Martinez Arsenal Members' Day 2015 (19929834919).jpg|thumb|left|David Ospina training alongside his Arsenal teammates [[Petr Čech]] and [[Emiliano Martínez]] in 2015]]
Ospina made his debut on 23 September 2014 in a 2–1 [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] loss to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/11116668/Arsenal-vs-Southampton-League-Cup-live.html |title=Arsenal vs Southampton: League Cup – live |publisher=The Telegraph |date=2014-09-23 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> His [[UEFA Champions League]] debut came on 1 October 2014 against [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], replacing [[Alexis Sánchez]] after [[Wojciech Szczęsny]] was sent off. Despite conceding a penalty, he helped Arsenal secure a 4–1 victory with several crucial saves.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/oct/01/arsenal-galatasaray-champions-league-match-report |title=Arsenal cruise as Danny Welbeck hat-trick sinks Galatasaray |work=The Guardian |date=2014-10-01 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

He sustained a thigh injury in October that ruled him out for the remainder of 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/arsenal-injury-update-david-ospina-out-for-three-months-as-thigh-injury-sidelines-goalkeeper-9818816.html |title=Arsenal injury update: David Ospina out for three months as thigh injury sidelines goalkeeper |work=The Independent |date=2014-10-24 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Upon recovery, Ospina returned in a 2–0 FA Cup win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and kept a clean sheet in his full Premier League debut, a 3–0 win over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/30740924 |title=Arsenal 3-0 Stoke City |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2015-01-11 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Following Szczęsny's internal disciplinary issues, Ospina became the Premier League starter, keeping further clean sheets against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. He played every league match thereafter, though he was an unused substitute in the 4–0 victory over Aston Villa in the [[2015 FA Cup final|FA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jan/18/manchester-city-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |title=Arsenal expose Manchester City's flaws in fine win at Etihad Stadium |work=The Guardian |date=2015-01-18 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/32943141 |title=Arsenal 4-0 Aston Villa |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2015-05-30 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

His performances earned him a place on the FIFA Ballon d’Or 2015 longlist.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/11961448/Ballon-dOr-2015-full-list-of-candidates.html |title=Ballon d'Or 2015: full list of candidates |publisher=The Telegraph |date=2015-10-29 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2015–16 season====
[[File:David Ospina, 2015-05-31 (cropped).JPG|thumb|upright|David Ospina with Arsenal after winning the [[2015 FA Cup final]]]]
Ospina featured in a 2–1 UEFA Champions League loss to [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] and a 2–1 League Cup win over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/sep/16/dinamo-zagreb-arsenal-champions-league-match-report |title=Arsenal suffer Champions League defeat as Dinamo Zagreb shock them |work=The Guardian |date=2015-09-16 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/34267499 |title=Tottenham 1-2 Arsenal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2015-09-23 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> A costly error in a 3–2 defeat to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] saw Ospina drop a corner into his own net, leading to his removal from Champions League duties.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/arsenal/arsenal-vs-olympiakos-match-report-david-ospina-s-own-goal-nightmare-leaves-champions-league-hopes-in-tatters-a6673416.html |title=Arsenal vs Olympiakos match report: David Ospina's own-goal nightmare leaves Champions League hopes in tatters |work=The Independent |date=2015-09-29 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

He also suffered a shoulder injury during international duty that sidelined him until November.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/34526367 |title=Arsenal goalkeeper David Ospina injures shoulder on international duty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2015-10-14 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2016–17 season====
Ospina served as Arsenal’s cup goalkeeper, starting in their opening Champions League group game against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]. He was named man of the match in a 1–1 draw for a standout performance, including several saves against [[Edinson Cavani]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/13/psg-arsenal-champions-league-match-report |title=David Ospina excels as Arsenal escape Paris Saint-Germain with a point |work=The Guardian |date=2016-09-13 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

He continued to feature in the Champions League and started all matches in Arsenal’s successful 2016–17 FA Cup run. In the final, Arsenal beat [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 2–1 at [[Wembley Stadium]], with Ospina making crucial saves including one against [[N'Golo Kanté]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39983944 |title=Arsenal 2-1 Chelsea |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2017-05-27 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2017–18 season====
Ospina remained the designated goalkeeper for the [[UEFA Europa League]] and domestic cups. His first appearance was a clean sheet in a 1–0 Carabao Cup win over [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41295989 |title=Arsenal 1-0 Doncaster Rovers |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2017-09-20 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

In the Europa League opener against [[1. FC Köln|FC Cologne]], he made an early error that led to the German side scoring first, but Arsenal recovered to win 3–1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/14/arsenal-fc-koln-europa-league-match-report |title=Arsenal brush aside Cologne despite early chaos in Europa League opener |work=The Guardian |date=2017-09-14 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Ospina's clean sheet in a 2–0 away win over [[A.C. Milan|AC Milan]] on 8 March 2018 in the Round of 16 helped restore form after four straight defeats.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43320643 |title=AC Milan 0-2 Arsenal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2018-03-08 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He also featured in the quarter-finals against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] and semi-finals against [[Atlético Madrid]].

While his shot-stopping ability remained strong, questions persisted about his aerial command. Arsenal were eventually eliminated by Atlético Madrid in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/may/03/atletico-madrid-arsenal-europa-league-semi-final-match-report |title=Atlético Madrid 1-0 Arsenal (agg 2-1): Europa League semi-final – as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=2018-05-03 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

=== Napoli ===
Following the arrival of [[Bernd Leno]] at [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], Ospina sought a loan move to secure more consistent playing time. On 15 August 2018, [[Serie A]] club [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] reached an agreement for a one-year loan deal with an option to buy, a decision influenced by an injury to newly signed goalkeeper [[Alex Meret]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/15/david-ospina-joins-napoli-on-loan-from-arsenal |title=David Ospina joins Napoli on loan from Arsenal |work=The Guardian |date=2018-08-15 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-a/napoli/2018/08/15-46747206/napoli_ufficiale_ospina_dal_arsenal_in_prestito_con_diritto_di_riscatto |title=Napoli, ufficiale Ospina dall'Arsenal in prestito con diritto di riscatto |publisher=Corriere dello Sport |date=2018-08-15 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2018–19 season====
Ospina quickly became a key figure in Napoli's squad, making 24 appearances across all competitions during his loan spell, including 17 in Serie A.<ref name="La Gazzetta dello Sport">{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/2019/07/04/napoli-ufficiale-il-riscatto-di-ospina-3401518764024.shtml |title=Napoli, ufficiale il riscatto di Ospina |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=2019-07-04 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He was noted for his composure and ball-playing ability, suiting Napoli's style under manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]]. A significant moment occurred on 17 March 2019, during a Serie A match against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]. Ospina suffered a serious head injury following a collision with striker [[Ignacio Pussetto]]. Despite treatment and briefly continuing with a bandage, he collapsed before halftime and was stretchered off and hospitalized. Scans revealed no serious damage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/napoli/2019/03/17/news/ospina_malore_campo-221764669/ |title=Napoli, Ospina malore in campo: la partita è sospesa |publisher=La Repubblica |date=2019-03-17 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/sport/calcio/ospina_malore_campo_napoli_udinese_cosa_e_successo-4366881.html |title=Ospina, malore in campo: il Napoli tranquillizza |publisher=Il Messaggero |date=2019-03-17 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

On 4 July 2019, Napoli exercised their option, permanently signing Ospina from Arsenal for a reported €3.5 million.<ref name="La Gazzetta dello Sport"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-a/napoli/2019/07/04-58586047/ospina_e_del_napoli_riscattato_dall_arsenal |title=Ospina è del Napoli: riscattato dall'Arsenal |publisher=Corriere dello Sport |date=2019-07-04 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2019–20 season====
In the 2019–20 season, Ospina rotated with [[Alex Meret]] but became first-choice under manager [[Gennaro Gattuso]] for his superior ball distribution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/07-03-2020/fragile-poco-funzionale-gioco-gattuso-napoli-c-caso-meret-3601518752389.shtml |title=Fragile e poco funzionale al gioco di Gattuso: al Napoli c'è il caso Meret |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=2020-03-07 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-a/napoli/2020/06/17-70275817/napoli_il_portiere_e_ospina_gattuso_ha_scelto |title=Napoli, il portiere è Ospina: Gattuso ha scelto |publisher=Corriere dello Sport |date=2020-06-17 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He made 23 appearances, including 17 in Serie A.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/2020/08/02/napoli-report-stagionale-di-ospina-3401518752389.shtml |title=Napoli: report stagionale di Ospina |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=2020-08-02 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

A pivotal moment came in the [[Coppa Italia]] semi-finals against [[Inter Milan|Inter]]. Ospina misjudged a corner, allowing [[Christian Eriksen]] to score directly, but later redeemed himself with key saves and assisted [[Dries Mertens]]’ equaliser via a long ball, securing a 2–1 aggregate win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/coppa-italia/2020/06/13-70094770/napoli-inter_1-1_gattuso_in_finale_meret_in_panchina_ospina_protagonista |title=Napoli-Inter 1-1, Gattuso in finale: Meret in panchina, Ospina protagonista |publisher=Corriere dello Sport |date=2020-06-13 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Suspended for the final, [[Alex Meret]] started as Napoli beat [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] 4–2 on penalties after a 0–0 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/coppa-italia/2020/06/17/news/napoli-juve_coppa_italia-259424687/ |title=Coppa Italia, il Napoli batte la Juve ai rigori e vince il trofeo |publisher=La Repubblica |date=2020-06-17 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2020–21 season====
Ospina remained a key figure during the 2020–21 campaign, making 23 appearances, including 16 in Serie A and recording 8 clean sheets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/2021/05/24/napoli-report-stagionale-di-ospina-3401518752389.shtml |title=Napoli: report stagionale di Ospina |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=2021-05-24 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He was vital in manager Gattuso’s possession-based tactics, known for calm distribution and control during transitions. Despite minor injuries, he was consistent in form. Napoli narrowly missed [[UEFA Champions League]] qualification, finishing 5th.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/2021/05/23/news/napoli_verona_champions_lega_risultato-302324907/ |title=Napoli-Verona 1-1, azzurri fuori dalla Champions |publisher=La Repubblica |date=2021-05-23 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Key teammates included captain [[Lorenzo Insigne]] and midfielder [[Piotr Zieliński]].

====2021–22 season====
The 2021–22 campaign was Ospina’s most active at Napoli. Under [[Luciano Spalletti]], he became the undisputed starter, making 33 appearances—31 in Serie A—with 13 clean sheets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-a/napoli/2022/05/22-94420836/napoli_ospina_i_numeri_della_stagione_e_il_futuro |title=Napoli, Ospina: i numeri della stagione e il futuro |publisher=Corriere dello Sport |date=2022-05-22 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He conceded just 25 goals in Serie A, averaging 0.81 goals per game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/2022/05/22/napoli-report-stagionale-di-ospina-3401518752389.shtml |title=Napoli: report stagionale di Ospina |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=2022-05-22 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Napoli finished 3rd, mounting a strong but ultimately unsuccessful title challenge. Ospina was praised for his leadership, positioning, and shot-stopping. He left the club as a free agent at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/napoli/2022/06/05/news/ospina_addio_napoli_meret_portiere-352994781/ |title=Napoli, Ospina ai saluti. Meret promosso titolare |publisher=La Repubblica |date=2022-06-05 |language=it |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

=== Al Nassr ===
Following his departure from [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] as a free agent, David Ospina made a significant move to Saudi Arabian club [[Al Nassr FC|Al Nassr]]. On 11 July 2022, the club officially announced his signing, bringing an experienced international goalkeeper to the [[Saudi Pro League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/sports/2022/07/11/Colombian-goalkeeper-David-Ospina-joins-Saudi-club-Al-Nassr |title=Colombian goalkeeper David Ospina joins Saudi club Al Nassr |publisher=Al Arabiya English |date=2022-07-11 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/football/2022/07/11/colombian-goalkeeper-david-ospina-signs-for-saudi-club-al-nassr/ |title=Colombian goalkeeper David Ospina signs for Saudi club Al Nassr |publisher=The National (Abu Dhabi) |date=2022-07-11 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2022–23 season====
Ospina quickly established himself as Al Nassr's first-choice goalkeeper for the 2022–23 season. He made 13 appearances in the [[Saudi Pro League]], contributing significantly to the team's strong defensive record, which saw them concede only six goals in the league matches he played.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://saudigazette.com.sa/article/630537/Sports/Al-Nassr-top-Saudi-Pro-League-after-Al-Hilals-loss |title=Al Nassr top Saudi Pro League after Al Hilal's loss |publisher=Saudi Gazette |date=2023-01-14 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> His performances included several clean sheets, showcasing his shot-stopping abilities and command of the penalty area. Ospina's arrival coincided with a period of significant ambition for Al Nassr, particularly highlighted by the signing of [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] in January 2023. Ronaldo's arrival brought global attention to the club and the Saudi league, and Ospina's experience proved valuable in a team featuring such a high-profile figure.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/sports/2023/01/01/-كرستيانو-رونالدو-يوقع-رسميا-مع-النصر-السعودي |title=Cristiano Ronaldo signs with Saudi club Al Nassr |publisher=Al Arabiya |date=2023-01-01 |language=ar |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

However, Ospina's season was cut short by a severe elbow injury sustained in a league match against [[Al-Shabab FC (Riyadh)|Al-Shabab]] on 14 January 2023. The injury required surgery and sidelined him for the rest of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://english.alarabiya.net/sports/2023/01/16/Al-Nassr-goalkeeper-David-Ospina-to-undergo-surgery-after-suffering-elbow-injury |title=Al Nassr goalkeeper David Ospina to undergo surgery after suffering elbow injury |publisher=Al Arabiya English |date=2023-01-16 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> His absence was a blow to Al Nassr's title challenge. Despite this, the club finished second in the Saudi Pro League, five points behind champions [[Al-Ittihad Club (Jeddah)|Al-Ittihad]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2313626/sport |title=Al-Ittihad win Saudi Pro League title |publisher=Arab News |date=2023-05-28 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> In the [[King Cup|King's Cup]], Ospina made one appearance before his injury; Al Nassr reached the semi-finals but were eliminated by [[Al-Wehda FC|Al Wehda]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/sports/2023/04/24/الشباب-والفيحاء-والوحدة-والاتحاد-في-نصف-نهائي-كأس-الملك-2023 |title=Al-Shabab, Al-Fayha, Al-Wehda and Al-Ittihad in King's Cup semi-finals 2023 |publisher=Al Arabiya |date=2023-04-24 |language=ar |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Other key players that season included [[Anderson Talisca]], the team's top scorer, and Ronaldo, who scored 14 league goals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2288076/sport |title=Talisca, Ronaldo on target as Al Nassr bounce back from Cup loss |publisher=Arab News |date=2023-04-19 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

====2023–24 season====
Ospina's 2023–24 season was heavily affected by the lingering effects of his elbow injury. He returned to action only in March 2024.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2471676/sport |title=Ronaldo leads Al Nassr to comfortable win over Al-Ain |publisher=Arab News |date=2024-03-05 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Due to his prolonged absence, he made only 11 appearances across all competitions, with just one in the Saudi Pro League.<ref name="Al Arabiya">{{cite news |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/sports/2024/05/28/رونالدو-يكسر-الرقم-القياسي-في-الدوري-السعودي-للمحترفين |title=Ronaldo breaks Saudi Pro League record |publisher=Al Arabiya |date=2024-05-28 |language=ar |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> During his absence, Al Nassr relied on other goalkeepers including [[Nawaf Al-Aqidi]] and [[Raghed Al-Najjar]].

Despite Ospina's limited involvement, Al Nassr had a high-profile campaign, finishing second in the Saudi Pro League for a second consecutive year—this time behind unbeaten rivals [[Al Hilal SFC|Al-Hilal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2517861/sport |title=Al-Hilal finish Saudi Pro League season unbeaten |publisher=Arab News |date=2024-05-28 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

Al Nassr made strides in cup competitions. They won the [[Arab Club Champions Cup]], although Ospina did not feature in the final due to injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2353346/sport |title=Ronaldo powers Al Nassr to Arab Club Champions Cup title |publisher=Arab News |date=2023-08-12 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> The team also reached the final of the King's Cup, where they lost to Al-Hilal on penalties after a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2522776/sport |title=Al-Hilal beat Al-Nassr on penalties to win King's Cup |publisher=Arab News |date=2024-05-31 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

In the [[AFC Champions League]], Al Nassr reached the quarter-finals but were eliminated by [[Al Ain FC|Al Ain]] in a penalty shootout. Ospina featured in the second leg, making a crucial save, but the team ultimately fell short.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alarabiya.net/sports/2024/03/12/العين-الإماراتي-يُقصي-النصر-السعودي-من-دوري-أبطال-آسيا |title=UAE's Al Ain eliminates Saudi's Al Nassr from AFC Champions League |publisher=Al Arabiya |date=2024-03-12 |language=ar |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

The season marked the continued integration of international signings like [[Marcelo Brozović]], [[Seko Fofana]], [[Alex Telles]], [[Sadio Mané]], [[Otávio (footballer, born 1995)|Otávio]], and [[Aymeric Laporte]], elevating the club’s profile in Asian football.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/2360431/sport |title=Al-Nassr's Saudi Pro League title hopes take hit with Al-Raed defeat |publisher=Arab News |date=2024-03-07 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Cristiano Ronaldo continued to be the team's leading scorer, breaking the Saudi Pro League record for most goals in a single season. Although Ospina's game time was limited, his experience remained valued within the squad.<ref name="Al Arabiya"/>

=== Return to Atlético Nacional ===
After a successful stint in Saudi Arabia with [[Al Nassr FC|Al Nassr]], David Ospina made an emotional return to his boyhood club, [[Atlético Nacional]], on 30 June 2024, joining on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/david-ospina-regresa-a-atletico-nacional-articulo-989255/ |title=David Ospina regresa a Atlético Nacional |publisher=El Espectador |date=2024-06-30 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elcolombiano.com/deportes/futbol/david-ospina-atletico-nacional-FC24089849 |title=¡Es oficial! David Ospina es nuevo arquero de Atlético Nacional |publisher=El Colombiano |date=2024-06-30 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> His return was met with considerable excitement by the club's supporters, as he was seen as a symbol of Atlético Nacional’s legacy and a major reinforcement for their ambitions.

Ospina's immediate impact was felt in the [[Copa Colombia]]. He played a crucial role in Atlético Nacional’s triumph in the 2024 edition of the tournament, securing his first-ever title in the competition. In the final, Atlético Nacional held a 3–1 aggregate advantage against [[América de Cali]], drawing the second leg 0–0. Ospina’s presence and leadership were vital in securing the clean sheet that sealed the title.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.futbolred.com/futbol-colombiano/copa-betplay/david-ospina-y-los-titulos-con-atletico-nacional-tras-ganar-la-copa-betplay-2024-231120 |title=David Ospina y los títulos con Atlético Nacional tras ganar la Copa BetPlay 2024 |publisher=Futbolred |date=2024-11-23 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.semana.com/deportes/articulo/atletico-nacional-campeon-de-copa-colombia-2024-david-ospina-protagonista-en-el-titulo-contra-america-de-cali/202411/ |title=Atlético Nacional, campeón de Copa Colombia 2024: David Ospina, protagonista en el título contra América de Cali |publisher=Semana |date=2024-11-23 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> He featured in six matches throughout the tournament and remained undefeated in all of them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.futbolred.com/futbol-colombiano/copa-betplay/david-ospina-y-los-titulos-con-atletico-nacional-tras-ganar-la-copa-betplay-2024-231120 |title=David Ospina y los títulos con Atlético Nacional tras ganar la Copa BetPlay 2024 |publisher=Futbolred |date=2024-11-23 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

== International career ==
David Ospina’s international journey began at the youth level, where he quickly demonstrated the talent that would define his senior career as one of Colombia’s most important and long-serving players.

Ospina received his first call-up to the national under-20 team for the [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]] held in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-1875152 |title=Colombia a Holanda con un equipo completo |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2005-06-03 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> At just 16 years old, he was the youngest member of the Colombian squad, a testament to his talent and recognition as a future star. Although he did not make an appearance during the tournament, being part of the squad at such a young age provided less experience, exposing him to the intensity of international youth football and the demands of representing his country on a global stage. The Colombian under-20 team, featuring other future senior internationals, reached the Round of 16, showcasing a strong generation of Colombian football talent.

Two years later, Ospina was a more seasoned presence for the [[2007 South American U-20 Championship]] in Paraguay. He played four matches in the competition, establishing himself as the first-choice goalkeeper for the under-20 side.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-2367468 |title=Colombia se fue de Paraguay sin Mundial Sub-20 |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2007-01-28 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Despite his individual efforts and growing maturity in goal, Colombia failed to qualify for the FIFA U-20 World Cup, marking the end of his opportunities in major youth tournaments. This period allowed him to build a strong foundation, working alongside other emerging talents such as [[Radamel Falcao]] and [[Fredy Guarín]], who would later become integral parts of the senior national team.

Ospina made his senior debut for the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]] as a substitute on 7 February 2007 in a 1–3 friendly defeat against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], marking the beginning of his senior international career.<ref name="El Tiempo"/><ref name="El Espectador"/> He was 18 years old at the time. His first competitive match for Colombia came during the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification]] campaign. On 17 November 2007, he started in a qualifier against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]], becoming the youngest goalkeeper to ever play for Colombia in a World Cup qualifier at 19 years old.<ref name="El Espectador"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-3806871 |title=Ospina, el arquero más joven en eliminatorias |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2007-11-18 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref> Throughout the qualification cycle for the 2010 World Cup, Ospina gradually cemented his place as Colombia’s primary goalkeeper. Although Colombia did not qualify for the tournament, Ospina’s performances were a beacon of consistency, particularly his shot-stopping ability and commanding presence, laying the groundwork for future success.
[[File:Brazil and Colombia match at the FIFA World Cup 2014-07-04 (2).jpg|right|thumb|Ospina in action during the quarter-finals of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] against Brazil]]
The [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]] campaign proved to be a defining period for Ospina and the Colombian national team. He was the undisputed first-choice goalkeeper under coach [[José Pékerman]], playing a crucial role in Colombia’s successful qualification for their first World Cup since 1998. Ospina’s defensive solidity was paramount, and his performances earned widespread praise. By the end of the qualifiers, he had conceded the fewest goals in the [[CONMEBOL]] section, a remarkable achievement highlighting his importance to a defensively well-organized Colombian side.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-13009592 |title=El muro de Colombia: David Ospina |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2013-10-18 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/david-ospina-en-el-top-5-de-los-arqueros-con-mas-goles-encajados-en-las-eliminatorias-al-mundial-de-qatar-articulo-953330/ |title=David Ospina, en el top 5 de los arqueros con más goles encajados en las Eliminatorias al Mundial de Qatar |publisher=El Espectador |date=2022-03-30 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

At the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil, Ospina played every minute of Colombia’s five matches and conceded four goals during the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-14193638 |title=Ospina, un muro en el Mundial de Brasil |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2014-07-06 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref name="El Espectador"/>

Ospina continued as Colombia’s starting goalkeeper at the [[2015 Copa América]] in Chile, where he made several critical saves, including a double save against [[Sergio Agüero]] and [[Lionel Messi]] during a 0–0 quarter-final draw against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]. Despite his heroics, Colombia lost in the penalty shootout.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/deportes/copa-america/messi-quiere-ganar-copa-america-con-argentina-nid1805727/ |title=Argentina le ganó a Colombia en los penales y está en semifinales de la Copa América |publisher=La Nación (Argentina) |date=2015-06-27 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.clarin.com/deportes/copa-america-2015/seleccion-argentina-messi-aguero-ospina-penales-nid_0_HyJ31j_XQe.html |title=El show de Ospina no le alcanzó a Colombia: Argentina lo eliminó por penales |publisher=Clarín |date=2015-06-27 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

At the [[Copa América Centenario]] in 2016, hosted in the United States, Ospina once again proved his value, making two key saves in the penalty shootout against Peru that helped Colombia advance to the semi-finals. Colombia went on to finish third in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/CMS-16629931 |title=Ospina, el héroe de la Copa América Centenario |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2016-06-18 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref name="El Espectador"/>
[[File:FWC 2018 - Round of 16 - COL v ENG - Photo 088.jpg|left|thumb|Ospina during the penalty shoot-out against England in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] Round of 16]]

During the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] qualification, Ospina remained Colombia’s first-choice goalkeeper. He started every match at the tournament in Russia, where Colombia reached the Round of 16. In the match against [[England national football team|England]], Ospina played a central role in a dramatic penalty shoot-out, though Colombia were ultimately eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/03/colombia-england-world-cup-match-report |title=England beat Colombia in dramatic shootout to reach World Cup quarter-finals |work=The Guardian |date=2018-07-03 |language=en |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref name="El Espectador"/> He maintained two clean sheets; in the group stage matches against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] and [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]].

He remained first-choice for the [[2021 Copa América]] in Brazil, helping Colombia secure third place. Ospina’s leadership and penalty-stopping abilities against Uruguay in the quarter-finals were once again vital to the team’s success.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/deportes/futbol-internacional/seleccion-colombia-david-ospina-figura-en-copa-america-706917 |title=Colombia gana el bronce en Copa América 2021 con Ospina figura |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2021-07-10 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-internacional/copa-america-2021-colombia-gano-el-tercer-puesto-y-se-despidio-con-un-triunfo-ante-peru-articulo/ |title=Copa América 2021: Colombia ganó el tercer puesto y se despidió con un triunfo ante Perú |publisher=El Espectador |date=2021-07-09 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

At the [[2024 Copa América]], held in the United States, Ospina was named to the squad, but due to injury and age considerations, he served as an experienced backup and locker room leader rather than a starter. [[Camilo Vargas]] took over on the pitch, but Ospina’s veteran presence and mentorship were credited by teammates and coaching staff as instrumental in Colombia’s runner-up finish.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/seleccion-colombia-la-convocatoria-a-copa-america-2024-para-david-ospina-y-james-rodriguez-946272 |title=Selección Colombia: la convocatoria a Copa América 2024 para David Ospina y James Rodríguez |publisher=El Tiempo |date=2024-06-15 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/david-ospina-y-su-rol-en-la-seleccion-colombia-en-la-copa-america-el-lider-silencioso-articulo/ |title=David Ospina y su rol en la selección Colombia en la Copa América: el líder silencioso |publisher=El Espectador |date=2024-07-10 |language=es |access-date=2025-05-29}}</ref>

==Style of play==
An agile, athletic, and acrobatic shot-stopper,<ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2129827-arsenal-transfer-news-david-ospina-deal-to-be-confirmed-imminently |title=Arsenal Transfer News: David Ospina Deal to Be Confirmed Imminently |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Akerman |first1=Nick |date=15 July 2014 |access-date=18 June 2020 }}</ref><ref name="Goalkeepers on the Rise">{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1777571-10-world-football-goalkeepers-on-the-rise |title=10 World Football Goalkeepers on the Rise |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Edwards |first1=Daniel |date=18 September 2013 |access-date=18 June 2020 }}</ref> Ospina is also known for his reflexes<ref name="Arsenal agree £3m deal">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/22/arsenal-sign-colombia-goalkeeper-david-ospina |work=The Guardian |title=Arsenal agree £3m deal with Nice for Colombia goalkeeper David Ospina |last1=Hytner |first1=David |date=22 July 2014 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref><ref name="The top 100 targets">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/0/transfer-rumours-top-100-targets-summer-transfer-window-20171/david-ospina/ |title=Transfer rumours: The top 100 targets in the summer transfer window 2017 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 July 2017 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref><ref name="mlssoccer"/> and his technical ability with his feet,<ref name="Ospina always had great feet">{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/154453/insigne-ospina-always-had-great-feet |title=Insigne: 'Ospina always had great feet!' |publisher=Football Italia |date=13 June 2020 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref><ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malfitano |first1=Mimmo |date=23 May 2020 |title=Ospina, il pupillo di Rino: "Io e Meret, sana competizione. E lui sarà uno dei più grandi portieri" |trans-title=Ospina, Rino's favourite: "Meret and I, healthy competition. And he will be one of the greatest goalkeepers" |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/23-05-2020/ospina-pupillo-gattuso-con-meret-sana-competizione-3701215711226.shtml |access-date=17 June 2020 |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=it}}</ref> as well as his distribution and ability to produce accurate throws,<ref name="Ospina always had great feet"/><ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper"/><ref name="league’s top goalkeeper">{{cite web |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2015/05/02/is-arsenals-ospina-the-leagues-top-goalkeeper-as-wenger-has-stat/ |title=Is Arsenal's Ospina the league's top goalkeeper, as Wenger has stated? |publisher=www.hitc.com |last1=Thomas |first1=Che |date=2 May 2015 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> which allows him to play the ball out from the back and start attacks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=D'Amato |first1=Claudio |date=16 January 2020 |title=Dualismo Meret-Ospina in casa Napoli: coi piedi meglio il colombiano |trans-title=The Meret-Ospina duality at Napoli: with his feet, the Colombian is better. |url=https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/meret-ospina-napoli-piedi/1imoivz4jp24r1dqnaaopmrzwe |access-date=17 June 2020 |publisher=Goal.com |language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicita |first1=Maurizio |date=16 January 2020 |title=Ospina, il prescelto di Gattuso: "Meret sarà un grande portiere" |trans-title=Ospina, Gattuso's chosen one: "Meret will be a great goalkeeper." |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/16-01-2020/napoli-ospina-prescelto-gattuso-meret-sara-grande-portiere-360148558357.shtml |access-date=17 June 2020 |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=it}}</ref> Considered by pundits to be a promising goalkeeper in his youth,<ref name="Goalkeepers on the Rise"/> his former Nice manager, Frédéric Antonetti, once described him as an "international-standard goalkeeper," also stating: "He has everything you need to be a top goalkeeper. He's good in the air and he's good on the ground. He has that little extra something to be a champion. Hugo Lloris was an international-standard goalkeeper; so is David."<ref name="Ospina Praised by Nice boss">{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/3912/english-premier-league/2014/07/27/4973986/david-ospina-the-man-who-replaced-hugo-lloris-meet-the-new|title=Ospina will be a success|publisher=Goal.com|date=27 July 2014|access-date=27 July 2014}}</ref><ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper">{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-au/news/4016/main/2014/07/22/4974564/meet-arsenals-next-goalkeeper-david-ospina |title=Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper David Ospina |publisher=Goal.com |date=22 July 2014 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> He is also known for his reserved character and calm demeanour on the pitch.<ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper"/> Although he was criticised in the media during his earlier career for being prone to rash errors, while his ability to command his area and decision-making about when to come off his line also came into question, he was able to improve in these areas as his career progressed due to his work-rate, in particular in his speed when rushing off his line and getting to ground to smother the ball&nbsp;– which makes him effective in one on one situations –, or when dealing with crosses;<ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper"/><ref name="The top 100 targets"/><ref name="mlssoccer">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/players/david-ospina |title=David Ospina |publisher=MLS Soccer |access-date=17 June 2020}}</ref><ref name="league’s top goalkeeper"/> as such, he has been described by journalists as a "[[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|sweeper keeper]]," due to his playing style and ability to rush out of goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2142795-arsenal-transfer-news-why-david-ospina-will-be-gunners-new-no-1 |title=Arsenal Transfer News: Why David Ospina Will Be Gunners' New No. 1 |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Newman |first1=Stuart |date=27 July 2014 |access-date=22 June 2020 }}</ref> However, despite his all-round improvement as he entered his prime, his tendency to commit errors has persisted, which has been a source of scrutiny from pundits.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/club/arsenal/359/blog/post/3473779/jan-oblaks-brilliance-highlights-arsenals-need-to-upgrade-at-goalkeeper-this-summer |title=Jan Oblak's brilliance highlights Arsenal's need to upgrade at goalkeeper this summer |publisher=ESPN FC |last1=McNicholas |first1=James |date=27 April 2018 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> Standing at 1.83&nbsp;m (6&nbsp;ft), Ospina is not particularly tall for a goalkeeper;<ref name="In praise of short">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/may/20/in-praise-of-shorter-goalkeepers-david-ospina-arsenal |title=In praise of short(er) goalkeepers |work=The Guardian |last1=Andrews |first1=Neil |date=20 May 2015 |access-date=17 June 2020}}</ref> as such, his lack of height has occasionally limited him in the air at times, despite his bravery.<ref name="Meet Arsenal's next goalkeeper"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/row-zed/dimitar-berbatov-v-david-ospina-5231031 |title=Dimitar Berbatov v David Ospina: Monaco's main man once made Arsenal's keeper look very silly |work=The Mirror |last1=Innes |first1=Richard |date=25 February 2015 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> He has also been accused of being inconsistent and unreliable in the media,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2018/05/05/arsenal-fans-on-twitter-want-jack-butland-signed-up/ |title=Arsenal fans on Twitter want Jack Butland signed up |publisher=www.hitc.com |last1=Callaghan |first1=Shane |date=5 May 2018 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/english-soccer/premier-league-who-needs-to-strengthen-where-1.2233518 |title=Premier League: Who needs to strengthen where? |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=1 June 2015 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> despite his excellent and consistent performances at international level.<ref name="The top 100 targets"/> Consequently, critical reception of Ospina has been divided; while his former Arsenal manager Wenger labelled him as the "best goalkeeper in the Premier League" in 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/11909585/Arsene-Wenger-defends-Arsenal-goalkeeper-David-Ospina.html |title=Arsene Wenger defends Arsenal goalkeeper David Ospina |work=The Daily Telegraph |last1=Collings |first1=Simon |date=3 October 2015 |access-date=18 June 2020 }}</ref> and as "a world-class goalkeeper" in 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/features/20160218/-a-goalkeeper-is-always-focused- |title=A goalkeeper is always focused |publisher=Arsenal |last1=Jones |first1=Max |newspaper=A Goalkeeper is Always Focused |date=25 February 2016 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> Michael Cummings of ''[[Bleacher Report]]'' instead stated in 2015 that "Ospina is not a top-class goalkeeper," despite performing well for Arsenal since earning the starting role over Szczęsny earlier that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2476753-david-ospina-error-underlines-arsenals-need-for-top-class-goalkeeper |title=David Ospina Error Underlines Arsenal's Need for Top-Class Goalkeeper |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Cummings |first1=Michael |date=27 May 2015 |access-date=17 June 2020 }}</ref> Former Arsenal goalkeeper [[Bob Wilson (footballer, born 1941)|Bob Wilson]] instead described him as a "solid keeper" in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/bob-wilson-backs-david-ospina-ahead-of-carabao-cup-final-appearance-36639203.html |title=Bob Wilson backs David Ospina ahead of Carabao Cup final appearance |work=The Belfast Telegraph |date=24 February 2018 |access-date=18 June 2020 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Ospina was brother-in-law to fellow Colombian international footballer [[James Rodríguez]], who married David's sister Daniela in 2011. However, they announced their separation in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/james-rod/1mugl77wy9d541exdz6rcd0eqt|title=James Rodriguez and wife Daniela Ospina announce separation |website=Goal.com|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> Ospina has been married to Colombian model Jesica Sterling since 2012, and has two children.<ref>{{cite news |date=26 January 2015 |title=David Ospina es padre por segunda vez |trans-title=David Ospina is a father for the second time |url=http://www.goal.com/es-co/news/4604/colombianos-en-inglaterra/2015/01/26/8340492/david-ospina-es-padre-por-segunda-vez |website=Goal.com |language=es}}</ref>

He acquired [[French nationality law|French nationality]] by naturalization in June 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ospina officiellement français |trans-title=Ospina officially French |url=https://www.ogcnice.com/fr/article/17401/ospina-officiellement-francais.html |access-date=2023-08-12 |website=OGC Nice |language=fr}}</ref>

